          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/gaussian_level_05.png"
               alt="Intermediate Gaussian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Gaussian level 5: mid-level blur diminishes fine pore structure while preserving the
            main highlight and shadow pattern around the orange’s volume.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/gaussian_level_10.png"
               alt="Coarser Gaussian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Gaussian level 10: the fruit is represented primarily by its smooth outline and a small
            number of broad tonal regions; detailed texture is largely absent.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/gaussian_level_15.png"
               alt="Very coarse Gaussian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Gaussian level 15: only very low-frequency information remains; the orange resembles a
            soft, uniformly shaded disc, illustrating the limit of strong low-pass filtering.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/laplacian_stack.png"
               alt="Contact sheet of Laplacian stack levels for the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Laplacian stack (all levels): small-scale bands capture the granular peel texture,
            whereas coarser bands contain only the broad transitions between fruit, table, and
            background.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/laplacian_level_00.png"
               alt="Fine-scale Laplacian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Laplacian level 0: highest-frequency band dominated by pore-like texture and the
            sharpest edges, with near-zero response in smooth interior regions.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/laplacian_level_05.png"
               alt="Intermediate Laplacian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Laplacian level 5: mid-frequency band emphasizing the main outline of the fruit and
            intermediate-scale variations along the boundary between fruit and background.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/laplacian_level_10.png"
               alt="Coarser Laplacian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Laplacian level 10: broad band in which only large-scale contrast changes survive,
            yielding soft rims around the fruit and table edge with minimal interior texture.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="iteration-belt__item">
          <img class="iteration-belt__image"
               src="media/two/3_stacks/orange/laplacian_level_15.png"
               alt="Very coarse Laplacian level of the orange">
          <figcaption class="iteration-belt__caption">
            Laplacian level 15: lowest-frequency band with weak, diffuse responses; most structure
            has migrated into the coarsest Gaussian levels that act as the residual base image.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="iteration-belt__outro">
      <p>
        The apple and orange stacks together illustrate how Gaussian and Laplacian decompositions
        separate images into complementary descriptions across scale. The Gaussian stacks record
        how each object approaches a smooth, low-frequency representation as blur increases,
        whereas the Laplacian stacks distribute edges and texture into distinct band-pass layers.
        Because the construction is linear and reconstructive—summing all Laplacian levels plus the
        coarsest Gaussian recovers the original image—it provides a principled basis for
        multi-resolution operations such as blending, tone manipulation, and detail transfer that
        act selectively on specific spatial scales.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
